eeman’s narratives were pervaded by anxieties about recapitulation. Ultimately, this study shows that Freeman’s scheme of universal history was based on the idea of conflict between Euro-Christendom and the Judeo-Islamic Orient, and this shaped his engagement with contemporary issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoriography. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2020. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aAryan.  aEmpire.  aFreeman.  aHistory.  aIslam.  aNorman Conquest.  aOttoman.  aRace.  aThomas Arnold.  aVictorian.1 aRandall, Vicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613582740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526135827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526135827/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles